	abstract = {Participating in the global value chains (GVCs) has become an important channel for countries to achieve economic upgrading. However, it remains unknown whether obtaining higher returns from functional upgrading in the GVCs is conducive to equitable distribution of domestic income. This study explores the mechanism of functional upgrading in the GVCs on inter - and intra - national inequality, aiming to provide a basis for decision - making that enables economies to obtain higher value returns from different functional upgrading prospects and facilitates equitable distribution of domestic income. The findings indicate that, firstly, upgrading to the upstream and downstream functions of GVCs with the densest intangible assets is conducive to reducing the benefit gap between a country and other countries. However, the positive economic consequences resulting from successful functional upgrading in GVCs have not translated into more equitable income distribution within the country, which will lead to increased income inequality. Secondly, while focusing on production functions can help alleviate income inequality within a country, it can have a negative impact on the distribution of value among countries. Finally, from the perspective of the impact mechanism, GVCs power and effective structural changes are the channels that influence the relationship between GVCs functional upgrading and inequality among and within countries. To balance the contradictory outcomes of GVCs functional upgrading on inter - and intra - national inequality, policymakers need to design a multi - dimensional policy framework that ensures consistency between outward foreign direct investment policies, industrial policies, and global value chain governance policies. © 2025 Elsevier B.V., All rights reserved.},
